Docker operations 

docker --version --> to check the version 
docker login  --> asks for username and password 
docker search --> eg: docker search ngnix 
docker pull  --> docker pull ngnix 
docker inspect --> to get the more image details (docker inspect image ngnix)

docker images - images 
docker images ls --> list of images 
docker ps --> will show the running state containers 
docker ps -a --> will show stopped containers also 

docker create --> to create a container using image (docker create ngnix)
docker start --> to start a created container (docker start <container_id or name>) 
docker stop --> will stop the container (docker stop <container_id or name>) gracefully shutdown 
docker run --> will create container and start ( docker run --name ngnix_test ngnix) (this will keep running if want to quit we have to pass keyboard arguments open a new terminal and and stop the container)

docker run -d --name ngnix_test ngnix --> detached mode (container will start and come out)

docker create --name test1 ngnix --> custom name 

docker kill --> if a container goes unresponsive or hang (docker kill ngnix_test) will forcefully shutdown 
docker exec --> docker exec -it nginx_test /bin/bash (execution interactive terminal)

docker rm --> docker rm ngnix_test (always first stop the container and then remove it)
docker rmi --> docker rmi ngnix (to remove image, reference images should also gets deleted)

Docker Networking 
Bridge 
The bridge driver creates an internal network within a single Docker host. containers placed within this network can communicate with each other but are isolated from containers, not on the internal network. bridge is the default driver when running single containers or when using docker-compose.
Host 
when using the host driver, the container shares the network stack of the Docker host-appearing as if the container is the host itself, from a networking perspective.
None 
The none driver simply disables networking for a container, making it isolated from other containers.

docker network ls --> to see the network in the docker 
docker run -d --name httpd01  -p 8080:80 httpd 
docker run -d --name http02 --net host httpd 
docker run -d --name http03  --net none https ( none will not communicate internally or externally)

Docker Volumes 
docker volumes ls --> to see the volumes 
docker volume inspect <volume_name> --> to see the detailed information 
default location for docker volumes 
cd /var/lib/docker/volumes/

docker rm $(docker ps -a -q) 
after deleting the container the volumes will be still present, if we need to delete  docker volume rm <volume_name> 

docker volume prune --> this will remove all local volume not used by at least one container.

docker volume create test_volume --> to create a volume 
docker volume inspect test_volume 

to mount 
